=== Why Negative Region is 110x Denser? ===

Hypothesis: gHash structure + sieve dispersion
==================================================

1. gHash output W has structure (Hypothesis 3):
   - W might tend to have certain residue classes
   - e.g., W ≡ 1 mod 2, W ≡ 1 mod 3, etc.
   - This makes W land in 'dense' residue classes

2. Sieve dispersion (levels 1-26):
   - After sieving, some residue classes have MORE survivors
   - If W is in a 'dense' class, then:
     W-k (negative) stays in dense class
     W+k (positive) might move to sparse class

3. Semiprime density varies by residue class:
   - Not all residue classes have same # of semiprimes
   - Some classes are 'richer' in semiprimes
   - gHash might bias W toward 'rich' classes

4. Combined effect:
   - W lands in 'dense' residue class (negative side)
   - Negative region: MANY semiprimes (dense)
   - Positive region: FEW semiprimes (sparse)
   - Result: 110x density ratio!

==================================================
This explains 99.1% vs 0.9% = 110x denser!
Not from scan order (which is shuffled)
It's from RESIDUE CLASS DISPERSION!

